const Q_CRK_2019_MODEL_I=[{"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The core of Saul's disobedience was that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he freed the Kenites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he refused to carry out God's assignment on eliminating the Amalekites</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he didn't perform the task of smiting the Amalekites to the letter</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he preserved the booty for himself</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the biblical story, Saul's disobedience was that he did not completely destroy the Amalekites and their livestock as God had commanded. Instead, he spared King Agag and the best of the sheep and cattle. This is best represented by option 3, 'he didn't perform the task of smiting the Amalekites to the letter'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : DISOBEDIENCE AND CONSEQUENCES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God instructed Saul to utterly destroy Amalek because</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">he abhors idolatory and all forms of unrighteousness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its people opposed the Israelites on the way, after departing Egypt</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">its people encouraged Israel to disobey God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samuel had prayed for its destruction</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in 1 Samuel 15, God commanded Saul to destroy the Amalekites because they opposed the Israelites when they were coming up from Egypt. This is best represented by option 2, 'its people opposed the Israelites on the way, after departing Egypt'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE : DISOBEDIENCE AND CONSEQUENCES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the most significant lessons from the emergence of Deborah as a leader is that?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">she not only prophesied but also advised Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gender difference isn't a limitation to leadership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">honesty and integrity are key to leadership</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">one needs to summon courage as a leader to solve problems</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The story of Deborah in the Bible (Judges 4-5) is a significant one as it shows a woman leading the Israelites, a role typically held by men. This suggests that gender difference isn't a limitation to leadership. The other options, while they may be true of Deborah's character and actions, are not the most significant lessons from her emergence as a leader.</div>", "topic": "LEADERSHIP QUALITIES : JUDGES - DEBORAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah prophesied God's punishment of the Israelites because they had</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">compromised HIs worship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">committed atrocities with their neighbours' wives</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">trampled on the needy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no belief in his message</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jeremiah, a prophet in the Bible, prophesied God's punishment of the Israelites because they had compromised His worship. This is seen in Jeremiah 2:13 where God, speaking through Jeremiah, accuses the Israelites of forsaking Him, the source of living water, and digging their own cisterns, broken cisterns that cannot hold water. This metaphorically refers to the Israelites abandoning the worship of God and turning to idols, which is a compromise of His worship. The other options do not accurately reflect the reasons for Jeremiah's prophecy.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE SITUATIONS THAT LED TO THE PUNISHMENT OF ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus healed the lame man who had been sick for thirty-eight years at?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Capernaum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Samaria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Galilee</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Bethsheba</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus healed the lame man who had been sick for thirty-eight years at the Pool of Bethesda, not in Capernaum, Samaria, Galilee or Bethsheba. The Pool of Bethesda is not listed as an option, hence the correct answer is not in the options provided.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah's vision and call indicates the following except that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God can not behold inquity</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God does not recognise man's inadequacies</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah witnessed the height of God's holiness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah confessed his unholiness</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah's vision and call in Isaiah 6:1-8 indicates that God is holy, Isaiah confessed his unholiness, and God cannot behold iniquity. However, it does not indicate that God does not recognize man's inadequacies. In fact, God's call and commissioning of Isaiah despite his confessed unholiness shows that God does recognize and have mercy on human inadequacies.</div>", "topic": "HOLINESS AND DIVINE CALL : THE CALL OF ISAIAH"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"For the men in the ship knew that he was fleeing from the presence of the Lord\". The person referred to in this statement is </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jonah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The person referred to in the statement \"For the men in the ship knew that he was fleeing from the presence of the Lord\" is Jonah. This is a reference to the biblical story of Jonah who tried to flee from God's command to go to Nineveh and preach against its wickedness. Instead, Jonah boarded a ship to Tarshish, but God sent a great storm. The sailors, realizing that Jonah's disobedience was the cause of the storm, threw him overboard.</div>", "topic": "GOD'S MESSAGE TO NINEVEH: JONAH AND HIS MESSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Israelites stood at ..... while Moses went up the mountain to receive God's commandments</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Mount Sinai</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Raphidim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the wilderness of Sin</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Horeb</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Israelites stood at Mount Sinai while Moses went up the mountain to receive God's commandments. This is a reference to the biblical event where Moses received the Ten Commandments from God on Mount Sinai, while the Israelites waited at the foot of the mountain. The other options, Raphidim, the wilderness of Sin, and Horeb, are other locations mentioned in the Bible, but they are not the correct answer to this question.</div>", "topic": "THE COVENANT : GOD'S COVENANT WITH ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah fed on ..... after declaring drought upon the land of Israel</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vine, wheat and water</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oath, barley and water</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bread, meat and water</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bread, fish and oil</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically 1 Kings 17:4-6, after Elijah declared a drought on the land of Israel, he was directed by God to hide by the Brook Cherith, where he was fed by ravens who brought him bread and meat in the morning and evening, and he drank from the brook. Therefore, the correct answer is 'bread, meat and water'.</div>", "topic": "THE SUPREMACY OF GOD : RELIGIOUS TENSION AND THE POWER OF GOD ON MOUNT CARMEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For how long did the Lord supply the children of Israel with manna in the wilderness?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thirty-eight years</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Forty years</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Eleven months</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Twenty two years</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically Exodus 16:35, the Israelites ate manna for forty years, until they came to a land that was inhabited; they ate manna until they came to the border of the land of Canaan. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Forty years'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on spiritual giifts was directed to the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macedonians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thessalonians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Corinthians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Galatians</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on spiritual gifts is found in his first letter to the Corinthians, specifically in 1 Corinthians 12. Here, he discusses the various spiritual gifts given by the Holy Spirit and emphasizes that while the gifts are different, they all come from the same Spirit and are given for the common good of the body of Christ, which is the church.</div>", "topic": "SPIRITUAL GIFTS : THE DIFFERENT SPIRITUAL GIFTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Paul's teaching on civic responsibility, a Christian is expected to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obey rulers without questioning</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">resist states' power over life and death of its citizens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be subject to the governing authorities</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be terror to any government not ordained by God</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Romans 13:1-7, Paul teaches about the Christian's responsibility towards the governing authorities. He states that every person should be subject to the governing authorities, for there is no authority except from God, and those that exist have been instituted by God. Therefore, Christians are expected to respect and obey the laws of the land, as long as these laws do not contradict the laws of God.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE NEED FOR OBEDIENCE TO AUTHORITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter advised the young, in his teaching on interpersonal relationship among Cristians to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">maintain good conduct among non-Christians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">subject themselves to the elders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">oppose unjust suffering</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">see themselves as strong and able-bodied servants of God</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In his teachings, Peter advised the young to maintain good conduct among non-Christians. This is because good conduct serves as a testimony to non-believers and can potentially lead them to Christ. This is found in 1 Peter 2:12 where Peter says 'Live such good lives among the pagans that, though they accuse you of doing wrong, they may see your good deeds and glorify God on the day he visits us.'</div>", "topic": "INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS : INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS AMONG CHRISTIANS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. James' teaching on impartiality centres on</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loving our neighbours as ourselves in all situations</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians not being partial to idle people</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giving the place of the rich to the poor in the church</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the rich spending their wealth on the poor for social equity</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. James' teaching on impartiality centres on loving our neighbours as ourselves in all situations. This is found in James 2:8-9 where James says 'If you really keep the royal law found in Scripture, \"Love your neighbor as yourself,\" you are doing right. But if you show favoritism, you sin and are convicted by the law as lawbreakers.' This means that we should not show favoritism or partiality, but should love everyone equally as we love ourselves.</div>", "topic": "IMPARTIALITY : CONCEPT OF IMPARTIALITY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's condition for the attainment of justification is by ...?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in the resurrected Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">total obedience to the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loving our Christian brethens</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">holiness in Christ Jesus</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament, particularly in the letters of Paul, justification is by faith in Jesus Christ. Paul consistently teaches that we are justified, or declared righteous, not by our works, but by faith in the finished work of Christ. This is evident in verses like Romans 3:28, 'For we hold that one is justified by faith apart from works of the law.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'faith in the resurrected Jesus'.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Moses named the place where the Israelites drank water from the rock 'Mesah and Meribah' particularly because...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they made him strike the rock angrily</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people had enough water to drink</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they wanted to put the Lord to test</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of their fault finding attitude</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Exodus 17:7, Moses named the place Massah (which means 'testing') and Meribah (which means 'quarreling') because the Israelites quarreled and tested the Lord there, saying, 'Is the Lord among us or not?' They doubted God's presence and provision, thus putting Him to the test. Therefore, the correct answer is 'they wanted to put the Lord to test'.</div>", "topic": "OBEDIENCE AND DISOBEDIENCE :EXAMPLES OF ADAM, COLLECTION OF MANNA, THE GOLDEN CALF, MOSES AND SAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cleopas' heart burnt within him on the road to Emmaus when Jesus</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">walked with them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">broke bread with them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appeared to them</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taught them the scriptures</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Luke 24:32, Cleopas and his companion's hearts burned within them when Jesus talked with them on the road and opened the Scriptures to them. This means that they felt a deep spiritual stirring or awakening as Jesus explained the Scriptures to them. Therefore, the correct answer is 'taught them the scriptures'.</div>", "topic": "RESURRECTION, APPEARANCES AND ASCENSION OF JESUS : THE RESURRECTION AND APPEARANCE OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"I gave you cleanness of teeth in all your cities\". By thiis statement, God gave them</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no food to eat</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">new set of teeth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no water to drink</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">no teeth at all</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase \"I gave you cleanness of teeth in all your cities\" is found in the book of Amos 4:6 in the Bible. It is a metaphorical way of saying that God had caused a famine. When there is no food, people's teeth are clean from not eating. Therefore, the correct answer is 'no food to eat'.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE SITUATIONS THAT LED TO THE PUNISHMENT OF ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The name, \"Jezreel\" is a representation of</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the punishment to come unto the royal house</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">victory upon the enemies of Israel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hosea's discontent with his wife</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the broken covenant between God and Israel</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Hosea, the prophet Hosea was instructed by God to marry a prostitute named Gomer as a symbolic act. They had three children, and one of them was named Jezreel. The name Jezreel is a representation of the punishment to come unto the royal house of Israel because of their idolatry and unfaithfulness to God. This is a prophetic symbolism where the names and lives of Hosea's family were used to send messages to the people of Israel.</div>", "topic": "PUNISHMENT AND HOPE : THE SITUATIONS THAT LED TO THE PUNISHMENT OF ISRAEL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter advised christians to ... as they were sharing Christ's sufferings</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be steadfast</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">persevere</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rejoice</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">be prayerful</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 4:13, Peter advised Christians to rejoice as they were sharing Christ's sufferings. He encouraged them to be glad for the privilege of suffering for Christ, as this would result in great joy when Christ's glory is revealed. This teaching is based on the Christian belief that suffering for the sake of Christ is a part of the Christian journey and is something to be embraced rather than avoided.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : PERSECUTION OF PAUL"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">\"It shall be neither mine nor yours; divide it\" what was to be divided?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah's mantle</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Solomon's kingdom</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus' garment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Live baby</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement \"It shall be neither mine nor yours; divide it\" was made by King Solomon during the judgement of the two women who were fighting over a live baby. This was a test by Solomon to determine the real mother of the child. The real mother would rather the child be given to the other woman than see her child killed. This story is found in 1 Kings 3:16-28.</div>", "topic": "DECISION-MAKING : THE WISDOM OF SOLOMON"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One derivative lesson from the story of Gehazi's greed is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">as servants of God we must endeavour not to readily demand gifts from those we help</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dishonesty should not have been a ground for cursing Gehazi with leprosy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">we can by ourselves, through materialism, cause the destruction of generations yet unborn </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">we should be wary of accepting gifts from the unrighteous</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The story of Gehazi's greed teaches us that our actions can have consequences not only for ourselves but also for our descendants. Gehazi, the servant of Elisha, lied to Naaman and took gifts from him after Elisha had refused any payment for healing Naaman of his leprosy. When Elisha found out, he cursed Gehazi and his descendants with leprosy. This story is found in 2 Kings 5:20-27.</div>", "topic": "GREED AND ITS EFFECTS : GEHAZI"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The model example in St. Paul's teaching on humility is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Abraham</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prophet Elijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Noah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">None of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In St. Paul's teaching on humility, the model example he used was Jesus Christ, not Abraham, Prophet Elijah or Noah. Therefore, none of the options provided is correct.</div>", "topic": "HUMILITY : MEANING AND REQUIREMENTS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on forgiveness primarily shows that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genuine forgiveness only comes from God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians must not institute a 'master-servant' relationship contract</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">subordinates must regard their superiors and vice-versa for forgiveness to thrive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philemon had unilaterally decided not to accept Onesimus back</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's teaching on forgiveness primarily shows that genuine forgiveness only comes from God. This is because God is the ultimate source of forgiveness and it is from Him that we learn to forgive others. The other options do not accurately represent St. Paul's teaching on forgiveness.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul had already boasted to the ... and for this reason he sent a reminder letter to the... on Christian giving</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philipians, Corinthians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Macedonians, Corinthians</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Thessalonians, Church in Achaia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Romans, Church in Antioch</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament, specifically in 2 Corinthians 8:1-5, St. Paul boasts about the generosity of the Macedonians to encourage the Corinthians to give generously as well. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Macedonians, Corinthians'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE TEACHINGS OF PAUL ON CHRISTIAN GIVING."}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the following is not a condition for effective prayer according to St. James</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perseverance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">steadfastness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lowliness</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the book of James in the New Testament, effective prayer requires faith (James 1:6), perseverance (James 1:12), and steadfastness (James 5:7-8). However, lowliness is not mentioned as a condition for effective prayer in the book of James, making it the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "EFFECTIVE PRAYER : THE REQUIREMENTS OF EFFECTIVE PRAYER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. James in the teaching on faith and work gave the analogy of </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a poor man with wretched clothing approaching the rich for help</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a hungry man who approached his fellow christian for help</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a man who looks himself in the mirror and appreciates God for that</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a man of little faith encouraging others to work</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James 2:2-4, James gave an analogy of a man with gold rings and fine clothing, and a poor man in shabby clothing coming into an assembly. The analogy was used to illustrate the sin of partiality, not about a poor man approaching the rich for help. However, among the given options, the closest is the first option which talks about a poor man with wretched clothing approaching the rich for help.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One significance of St. Paul's teaching on 'Resurrection' is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">as Christ rose and ascended into glory, so as also must uphold the observance of the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians must not underestimate the power of baptism by immersion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the foundation of their hope of salvation is in Christ's resurrection</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the second coming of Christ is near</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Corinthians 15:12-19, St. Paul's teaching on 'Resurrection' emphasizes that if Christ has not been raised, then our preaching is in vain and your faith is in vain. This implies that the foundation of Christian hope of salvation is in Christ's resurrection. Therefore, the third option is the correct answer.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE RESURRECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To St. Paul, Christians can prepare for the second coming of Chirst by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being prayerful and watchful</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spreading the message of Christ's coming far and wide</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteous living</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">relentlessly fasting and praying</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the New Testament, St. Paul often emphasizes the importance of being prayerful and watchful in preparation for the second coming of Christ. This is seen in verses such as 1 Thessalonians 5:6, 'So then, let us not be like others, who are asleep, but let us be awake and sober.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'being prayerful and watchful'.</div>", "topic": "THE SECOND COMING OF CHRIST : PREPARATION FOR HIS COMING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The model example for wives in Christian families according to St. Peter is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Deborah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Sarah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rebecca</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ruth</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In 1 Peter 3:1-6, St. Peter uses Sarah, the wife of Abraham, as a model example for wives in Christian families. He commends her obedience to her husband and her inner beauty. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Sarah'.</div>", "topic": "INTERPERSONAL RELATIONSHIPS : RELATIONSHIP IN THE CHRISTIAN FAMILY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The core of St. Paul's advice on dignity of labour is that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians must work hard to actively support the Church and themselves</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Christians must be productive</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the lazy people must be made to learn in the hardest way possible</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">everyone should actively contribute to social progress</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The core of St. Paul's advice on dignity of labour is that Christians must work hard to actively support the Church and themselves. This is based on the biblical teaching that everyone should earn their own living and contribute to the welfare of the community, including the Church. This concept is often referred to as the 'dignity of labour', which emphasizes the importance of every job or task, no matter how menial or mundane it may seem.</div>", "topic": "DIGNITY OF LABOUR : CONCEPT OF DIGNITY OF LABOUR"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Peter's teaching on 'Civic Responsibility' centers upon</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social advancement </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">good citizenship</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">social justice </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">good neighbourliness</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Peter's teaching on 'Civic Responsibility' centers upon good citizenship. This is based on the biblical teaching that Christians should respect the authorities, obey the laws of the land, and contribute to the welfare of the society. This concept is often referred to as 'civic responsibility', which emphasizes the role of individuals in maintaining a healthy and functioning society.</div>", "topic": "CIVIC RESPONSIBILITY : THE REQUIREMENTS OF GOOD CITIZENSHIP."}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul's epistle to the Philippians on 'Christian Giving' indicated his reception of gifts from them through</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Church in Achaia</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Epaphroditus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Church in Corinth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Peter</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Philippians, St. Paul acknowledges the gifts he received from the Philippians through Epaphroditus. Epaphroditus was a fellow Christian from the city of Philippi who delivered the gifts to Paul and stayed with him to help him during his imprisonment (Philippians 2:25-30).</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIAN GIVING : THE IMPORTANCE OF CHRISTIAN GIVING"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul showed commitment as a means upon which forgiveness can effectively thrive by</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">converting Onesimus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">asking that Philemon to charge to his account whatever Onesimus owed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">appealing to Philemon to forgive Onesimus and accept him back as a brother</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">instructing Philemon to write off all the debts of Onesimus, if any, compassionately  </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of Philemon, St. Paul writes a letter to Philemon asking him to forgive Onesimus, a slave who had wronged him and run away. Paul had met Onesimus while in prison and had converted him to Christianity. In his letter, Paul asks Philemon to charge to his account whatever Onesimus owed him (Philemon 1:18). This shows Paul's commitment to forgiveness and reconciliation.</div>", "topic": "FORGIVENESS : PAUL’S TEACHING ON FORGIVENESS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to St. Paul, God sent the spirit of His son into men's hearts ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">crying, \"Abba! Father!\"</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">for purification</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">for the redemption of their sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">so that become and act like God</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Galatians 4:6, St. Paul wrote, 'Because you are sons, God sent the Spirit of his Son into our hearts, the Spirit who calls out, \"Abba, Father.\"' Therefore, the correct answer is 'crying, \"Abba! Father!\"'.</div>", "topic": "CHRISTIANS AS JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST : HOW CHRISTIANS ARE JOINT HEIRS WITH CHRIST"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Summarily, St. Paul in his teaching on 'New Life in Christ' advised Christians to</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dwell richly in the word of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">endeavour to be baptised by immersion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">forsake only adultery and murder</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pray for the grace of God</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Colossians 3:16, St. Paul advised, 'Let the word of Christ dwell in you richly in all wisdom; teaching and admonishing one another in psalms and hymns and spiritual songs, singing with grace in your hearts to the Lord.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'dwell richly in the word of God'.</div>", "topic": "NEW LIFE IN CHRIST : CONDITIONS AND BENEFITS OF NEW LIFE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'Abraham's faith was reckoned to him as righteousness'. This underscores St. Paul's admonition that </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">obedience of the law is unnecessary as compared to God's grace</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">justification is by faith and not the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">redemption in Christ is possible through observance of the law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith without work is fruitless</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The statement 'Abraham's faith was reckoned to him as righteousness' is a key theme in St. Paul's letters, particularly in Romans and Galatians. St. Paul uses Abraham's faith as an example to illustrate that justification is by faith and not by the law. This is because Abraham was considered righteous because of his faith in God, even before the law was given. Therefore, the correct answer is 'justification is by faith and not the law'.</div>", "topic": "JUSTIFICATION BY FAITH : MEANING AND BASIC CONDITIONS FOR JUSTIFICATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">St. Paul, in 'Law and Grace', although man was condemned, he has been redeemed through the</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">compliance to the laws of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">faith in Christ Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">grace of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">righteousness of his deeds</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In St. Paul's teaching on 'Law and Grace', he emphasizes that although man was condemned due to sin, redemption has been made possible through faith in Christ Jesus. This is a central theme in his letters, particularly in Romans and Galatians. He argues that the law could not save man, but through faith in Christ Jesus, man can be justified and redeemed. Therefore, the correct answer is 'faith in Christ Jesus'.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter healed Aeneas who had been bedridden for ... years</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">four</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eight</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">six</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">twelve</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in Acts 9:32-35, it is mentioned that Peter healed Aeneas who had been bedridden for eight years due to paralysis. Therefore, the correct answer is 'eight'.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The accusation of blasphemy against Moses, the Law and God was levied against </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Peter and John</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Paul</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Stephen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Philip</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Acts 6:8-15, Stephen was falsely accused of blasphemy against Moses, the Law, and God. The members of the Synagogue of the Freedmen were unable to resist the wisdom and the Spirit by which Stephen spoke, so they secretly induced men to say, 'We have heard him speak blasphemous words against Moses and God.' Therefore, the correct answer is 'Stephen'.</div>", "topic": "OPPOSITION TO THE GOSPEL MESSAGE : THE MARTYRDOM OF STEPHEN"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the folowing was not considered as a criteria for the selection of the 12th disciple</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">witnessing the baptism of Jesus Christ by John the baptist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">witnessing Christ's resurrection and ascension</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">possessing the gift of speaking in tongues</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taking care of the needs of the Christian community</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The criteria for the selection of the 12th disciple, as stated in the book of Acts, were that the person must have been with Jesus from the time of his baptism by John until his ascension, and must be a witness of his resurrection. The gift of speaking in tongues was not a requirement for the selection of the 12th disciple. Speaking in tongues is a spiritual gift that was given to the disciples at Pentecost, after the selection of the 12th disciple.</div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE TWELVE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus' charged Christians to express love just as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they would do with their neighbours</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He taught them the new commandment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they love God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He laid his life for the sake of mankind</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In John 15:12, Jesus commands his followers to love one another as he has loved them. The ultimate demonstration of Jesus' love was his willingness to lay down his life for mankind. Therefore, Jesus charged Christians to express love just as he laid his life for the sake of mankind.</div>", "topic": "LOVE : LOVE FOR ONE ANOTHER"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The triumphal entry was in fulfilment of the prophecy of ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Zechariah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Isaiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Elijah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Amos</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The prophecy of the triumphal entry of Jesus into Jerusalem is found in the book of Zechariah 9:9. The prophecy states: 'Rejoice greatly, Daughter Zion! Shout, Daughter Jerusalem! See, your king comes to you, righteous and victorious, lowly and riding on a donkey, on a colt, the foal of a donkey.' This prophecy was fulfilled as recorded in the New Testament books of Matthew 21:1-11, Mark 11:1-11, Luke 19:28-44, and John 12:12-19.</div>", "topic": "THE TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE : TRIUMPHAL ENTRY AND THE CLEANSING OF THE TEMPLE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The disciples immediately understood, when they asked Jesus 'why the scribes said Elijah will come first', that He was symbolically referring to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the appearance of Elijah at His transfiguration</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">John the Baptist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His second coming after resurrection</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the people's refusal to accept Him as the Messiah</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Matthew 17:10-13, the disciples asked Jesus why the scribes said that Elijah must come first. Jesus replied that Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him but did to him whatever they pleased. Then the disciples understood that he was speaking to them about John the Baptist. This indicates that Jesus was symbolically referring to John the Baptist as the Elijah who was to come before the Messiah.</div>", "topic": "THE TRANSFIGURATION : THE EVENTS LEADING TO THE TRANSFIGURATION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the synoptic account of Luke, Jesus instructed that when the Seventy entered any town, they should do all but one of the following</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eat and heal the sick in any town they were received</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">carry no purse, bags, sandals and greet no one on the road</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">preach in the cities of Bethsaida and Capernaum saying, 'the kingdom of God has come near to you'</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">greet each household saying, 'peace be to this house'</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Gospel of Luke, Jesus sends out the Seventy (or Seventy-Two) in pairs to every place he himself intended to go, instructing them to heal the sick and say 'The kingdom of God has come near to you.' However, there is no specific mention of Jesus instructing them to preach in the cities of Bethsaida and Capernaum. Therefore, the correct answer is option 3.</div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE SEVENTY"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A Christian can demonstrate that he is a light of the world by </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being merciful to persons in need</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">upholding good moral values</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">being committed to improving himself</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">advocating for the meek to inherit the earth</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Sermon on the Mount, Jesus tells his followers that they are the light of the world, and that a city built on a hill cannot be hidden. This metaphor is often interpreted to mean that Christians should live their lives in such a way that their good deeds shine out for all to see, thereby glorifying God. Upholding good moral values is a key part of this, as it involves living in a way that is consistent with the teachings of Jesus. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2.</div>", "topic": "JESUS' TEACHINGS ABOUT HIMSELF : THE LIGHT OF THE WORLD"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the seed growing secretly is a parable illustrating</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">God's love for mankind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the Kingdom of God</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that there is time and season for everything</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concern for one another</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The parable of the seed growing secretly is a parable illustrating the Kingdom of God. In this parable, Jesus explains that the Kingdom of God is like a seed that grows secretly, without the farmer knowing how. This represents the mysterious and powerful growth of God's Kingdom on earth.</div>", "topic": "THE PARABLES : PARABLES OF THE KINGDOM"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the most significant lessons from the healing of the Centurion's Servant is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jesus has the power to forgive sins</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the salvation of God is universal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the level of faith of the servant made Jesus heal him</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">even the sons of the kingdom are not worthy of God's kingdom</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the most significant lessons from the healing of the Centurion's Servant is that the salvation of God is universal. In this story, Jesus heals the servant of a Roman Centurion, a non-Jew, showing that God's salvation is not limited to the Jews but is available to all people, regardless of their nationality or status.</div>", "topic": "MIRACLES : HEALING MIRACLES"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According of Luke, Jesus was standing by the ... He thereafter entered into the boat preaching and later 'calling' Simon Peter</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sea of Galilee</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lake of Gennesaret</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">City of Capernaum</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wall of Bethsaida</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Gospel of Luke, specifically Luke 5:1-3, Jesus was standing by the Lake of Gennesaret, also known as the Sea of Galilee. He entered into one of the boats, which was Simon's, and asked him to put out a little from the land. And He sat down and taught the people from the boat. Therefore, the correct answer is 'Lake of Gennesaret'.</div>", "topic": "MISSION OF THE DISCIPLES : THE MISSION OF THE TWELVE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The intent of the third temptation of Christ was to </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make Him see the riches of the world from a high mountain</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make Him seem like a magician</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make Him a political Messiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">make Him focus on wordly possessions</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The third temptation of Christ, as described in Matthew 4:8-10, involved the devil taking Jesus to a very high mountain and showing Him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory. The devil then offered to give all of these to Jesus if He would fall down and worship him. Therefore, the intent of the third temptation was to make Jesus see the riches of the world from a high mountain.</div>", "topic": "THE BAPTISM AND TEMPTATION OF JESUS : THE TEMPTATIONS OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>51", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">On the ... day, the child was ... and named Jesus</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eighth, anointed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">eighth, circumcised</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ninth, anointed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ninth, circumcised</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to the Bible, specifically in the book of Luke 2:21, it was on the eighth day that the child was circumcised and named Jesus. This was in accordance with Jewish law and tradition.</div>", "topic": "THE BIRTH AND EARLY LIFE OF JESUS : THE BIRTH AND BOYHOOD OF JESUS"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>52", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Faith and power was manifested in the reign of ... through ...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar; Shadrach, Meschack and Abednego </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Darius; Daniel</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Darius; Shadrach, Meschack and Abednego</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Nebuchadnezzar; Daniel</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in the book of Daniel, it is recorded that faith and power were manifested in the reign of Darius through Daniel. This is seen in Daniel 6 where Daniel was thrown into the lions' den for his faith, but God shut the mouths of the lions and Daniel was unharmed. This demonstrated both Daniel's faith and God's power.</div>", "topic": "FAITH, COURAGE AND PROTECTION : EXAMPLES OF DANIEL, SHADRACH, MESHACH AND ABEDNEGO"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>53", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Josiah sent ... the priest to inquire of the Lord from Huldah</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hilkiah</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Shaphan</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Shallim</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Hildah</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the Bible, specifically in 2 Kings 22:13, it is recorded that King Josiah sent Hilkiah the priest along with Ahikam, Achbor, Shaphan, and Asaiah to inquire of the Lord from the prophetess Huldah. However, the question specifically asks who the priest was that Josiah sent. The priest was Hilkiah, but since the question is asking for the priest that was sent to inquire of the Lord from Huldah, the correct answer is Shaphan, as he was the scribe who read the book of the law to Josiah and was sent to Huldah.</div>", "topic": "RELIGIOUS REFORMS IN JUDAH : RENEWAL OF THE COVENANT"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>54", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Lord protected the Israelites with all but one of the following when the Egyptians chased them</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pillar of storm</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pillar of cloud</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pillar of darkness</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">angels</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In Exodus 13:21-22, it is recorded that the Lord protected and guided the Israelites with a pillar of cloud by day and a pillar of fire by night when they were leaving Egypt. There is no biblical record of a 'pillar of storm' or 'angels' being used to protect the Israelites during their exodus from Egypt. Therefore, the correct answer is 'pillar of storm' as it is not one of the ways God protected the Israelites when the Egyptians chased them.</div>", "topic": "DIVINE PROVIDENCE, GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION :GUIDANCE AND PROTECTION"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>55", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">According to St. James, 'he who keeps the whole law and fails in one is guilty of ...'</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">breaking the whole law</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">breaking the ten commandments</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">breaking the new commandment of Chist</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">breaking that particular love and should pray for grace</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the book of James 2:10, it is written that 'For whoever keeps the whole law and yet stumbles at just one point is guilty of breaking all of it.' This means that if a person fails in one law, he is considered as breaking the whole law. Therefore, the correct answer is 'breaking the whole law'.</div>", "topic": "THE LAW AND GRACE : THE PURPOSE AND SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAW AND GRACE"}, {"id": "objective>CRK>2019 Model I>56", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The significance of the last supper is evident in all but one of the following</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">prediction of the suffering and death of Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the prophecy of Peter's denial of Jesus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the revelation of Judas' betrayal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">re-establishment of the Lord's covenant with his children</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Last Supper is significant for several reasons, including the prediction of Jesus' suffering and death, the revelation of Judas' betrayal, and the re-establishment of the Lord's covenant with his children. However, the prophecy of Peter's denial of Jesus, while it occurred around the same time, is not directly related to the significance of the Last Supper itself. Therefore, the correct answer is 'the prophecy of Peter's denial of Jesus'.</div>", "topic": "THE LAST SUPPER : THE SIGNIFICANCE OF THE LAST SUPPER."}];
